  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are schedules in the Indian constitution?",
  "response": "In the Indian Constitution, schedules are essentially appendices or annexures that provide additional details and elaborate on various aspects of the Constitution. They are an integral part of the Constitution and cover a range of topics, including lists of states and union territories, forms of oaths, and languages recognized by the Constitution.\n\nOriginally, there were **8 schedules** in the Indian Constitution when it was adopted in 1950. However, through various amendments, the number of schedules has increased to **12** as of now. Below is an overview of the 12 schedules in the Indian Constitution:\n\n---\n\n### **1. First Schedule**  \nLists the **States** and **Union Territories** of India and their respective territories.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Second Schedule**  \nContains provisions related to the **emoluments, allowances, and privileges** of key constitutional officers such as:  \n- President of India  \n- Governors of States  \n- Judges of the Supreme Court and High Courts  \n- Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG)  \n\n---\n\n### **3. Third Schedule**  \nContains the **forms of oaths and affirmations** for various constitutional positions, including:  \n- President  \n- Judges of the Supreme Court and High Courts  \n- Members of Parliament (MPs)  \n- State legislators  \n\n---\n\n### **4. Fourth Schedule**  \nAllocates seats in the **Rajya Sabha (Council of States)** to each State and Union Territory.  \n\n---\n\n### **5. Fifth Schedule**  \nDeals with the administration and control of **Scheduled Areas** and **Scheduled Tribes** in states other than Assam, Meghalaya, Tripura, and Mizoram.  \n\n---\n\n### **6. Sixth Schedule**  \nProvides for the administration of **tribal areas** in the states of Assam, Meghalaya, Tripura, and Mizoram through autonomous district councils.  \n\n---\n\n### **7. Seventh Schedule**  \nDivides the powers between the **Union** and the **States** into three lists:  \n1. **Union List** (subjects under the exclusive jurisdiction of the central government)  \n2. **State List** (subjects under the exclusive jurisdiction of state governments)  \n3. **Concurrent List** (subjects under the jurisdiction of both the central and state governments)  \n\n---\n\n### **8. Eighth Schedule**  \nLists the **official languages** recognized by the Constitution. Initially, it had 14 languages, but now it includes **22 languages**.  \n\n---\n\n### **9. Ninth Schedule**  \nContains a list of **laws and regulations** that are immune from judicial review. This schedule was added by the **First Amendment Act, 1951** to protect certain land reform laws.  \n\n---\n\n### **10. Tenth Schedule**  \nDeals with the **anti-defection law** for Members of Parliament and State Legislatures. It was added by the **52nd Amendment Act, 1985**.  \n\n---\n\n### **11. Eleventh Schedule**  \nLists the **powers, authority, and responsibilities of Panchayats** (rural local self-governments). It was added by the **73rd Amendment Act, 1992**.  \n\n---\n\n### **12. Twelfth Schedule**  \nLists the **powers, authority, and responsibilities of Municipalities** (urban local self-governments). It was added by the **74th Amendment Act, 1992**.  \n\n---\n\nThese schedules provide detailed information and act as a reference point for understanding specific provisions of the Constitution.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
